<P>The Lecture Notes referred to in this Learning Plan are <B>Chapter 2 ‘Algebra’</B>.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Linear Equations</P></B></FONT>
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>

<P>A linear equation takes the general form, ax + b = 0 where a and b are real numbers with a <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#185;</FONT>
 0 and x is the unknown variable.   The following are examples of linear equations:</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">3x + 4 = 0</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">-2n + 1 = 3</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">½ y – ¾  = 2</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">0.34p + 0.56 = 0.82</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">3z = 10</P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER"></P>
<P ALIGN="CENTER">4m – 6 = 5 – 2m</P>

<B><P>Note</P>
</B>
<OL TYPE="i">

<LI>In a linear equation the power of the variable is 1, since x = x<SUP>1</SUP>.</LI>
<LI>The unknown variable does not need to be x.</LI>
<LI>The equation may not be written in general form.</LI></OL>

<P>Solving a linear equation is illustrated on page 1 of your lecture notes.  
Try <a href="launch.htm#q0607">q0607</a> and <a href="launch.htm#q0369">q0369</a>.</P>

<P>If you feel you need to revise the basics of solving linear equations then work through the Learning Plan<B> "Linear Equations"</B> in <B>Test 3 Revision</B>.

<P>Many real life situations can be modelled by a linear relationship.</P>

<br>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=3><P>Example 1</P></B></FONT>
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>
<P>The prenatal growth of a foetus more than 12 weeks old can be approximated by the linear relationship</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">1.53t – 6.7 = L</P>

<P>in which L is the length in cm and t is the age in weeks.</P>

<P>If the length is estimated at 20cm use this relationship to estimate the age of the foetus.</P>

<B><P>Solution</P></B>
<P>L = 20</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 1.53t – 6.7 = 20</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 1.53 t = 26.7</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 t = 17.5 weeks </P>

<P>The foetus is approximately 17½ weeks old.</P>

<br>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=3><P>Example 2</P></B></FONT>
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>

<P>The relationship between the temperature F on the Fahrenheit scale and the temperature C on the Celsius scale is given by</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">C = 5/9(F – 32)</P>

<P>(i) If the temperature is 24<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#176;</FONT>
C calculate the equivalent temperature in Fahrenheit.</P>
<P>(ii) Find the temperature at which the reading is the same on both scales.</P>

<B><P>Solution</P></B>
<B><P>(i) </B>C = 24</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 24 = 5/9(F – 32) </P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 5/9(F – 32) = 24</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 5(F – 32) = 216</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 5F – 160 = 216</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 5F = 376</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 F = 75.2</P>

<P>A temperature of 24<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#176;</FONT>
C is equivalent to 75.2<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#176;</FONT>
F. </P>

<B><P>(ii)</B> C = F</P>

<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 F = 5/9(F – 32) </P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 9F = 5(F – 32)</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 9F = 5F – 160</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 4F = -160</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 F = -40</P>

<P>Hence -40<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#176;</FONT>
C is equivalent to -40<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#176;</FONT>
F.</P>

<P>A linear equation can be helpful when trying to calculate the concentration of a liquid.    Read through Example 2 in your lecture notes on page 1.  Now try <a href="launch.htm#q0697">q0697</a>.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
</FONT><B><FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=4><P>Straight Line Graphs</P></B></FONT>
<FONT FACE="Arial" SIZE=2>

<P>A linear relationship can be illustrated pictorially by a straight line graph.  Consider once again the age and length of a foetus.</P>

<P>The prenatal growth of a foetus more than 12 weeks old can be approximated by the linear relationship</P>

<P ALIGN="CENTER">1.53t – 6.7 = L</P>

<P>in which L is the length in cm and t is the age in weeks.</P>

<P>To assist with the construction of the graph of this linear relationship set up a table of values. </P>

<UL>
<LI>choose appropriate values for t</LI>
<LI>substitute the value for t in the relationship</LI>
<LI>calculate the corresponding value for L</LI></UL>

<P>eg </P>
<P>t = 12 </P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
 1.53(12) – 6.7 = L</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
18.36 – 6.7 = L</P>
<P><FONT FACE="Symbol">&#222;</FONT>
L = 11.66</LI></P>

<br>
